author: Samir Knox Wyoming Tribune Eagle
title: Wyoming unemployment up slightly, but economy improves in 2023 | News | wyomingnews.com
text: CHEYENNE — Wyoming, and the United States as a whole, outperformed economic projections in 2023, one of the state’s top economists said Wednesday. Despite a slight increase in the state’s unemployment rate, Wenlin Liu said that the economy could be headed for a “soft landing” in the new year. Liu, chief economist with the Wyoming Department of Administration and Information’s Economic Analysis Division, said that the state’s economy seemed to fare better than the rest of the country. “Wyoming’s economy continues to perform well, actually,” Liu told the Wyoming Tribune Eagle. “As far as the labor market ... it’s really ‘tight,’ which means that unemployment rate is low. It’s the lowest since summer 2008.” According to a report published by the Wyoming Department of Workforce Services on Tuesday, unemployment in the state rose slightly in the past few months, from 2.9% in October to 3% in November. The report did note that it was much lower than in November of 2022, when unemployment was at 3.9%. Wyoming’s unemployment rate currently sits well below the current national average of 3.7%, the report noted. Liu continued by saying that Wyoming’s economy showed broad growth overall, with growth in a number of different areas, including tourism. He did note a slowing of growth in retail and financial activities. He said the slower-than-average growth in the sector of financial activities, which includes loans and property sales, could be due to rising interest rates applied by the Federal Reserve throughout 2023. “The higher interest rate is trying to drive down inflation,” Liu said. “You have to pay higher (interest on) loans if you’re trying to buy a big item like an automobile, or even purchasing a house. Particularly, the housing market is slow, and business is facing a higher interest rate, and you’re trying not to expand your business much because, with high interest rates, you have to borrow more money. “I think in 2024 that high interest rate will negatively impact the economy, will slow down econom(ic) performance,” Liu continued. “That’s why we expect 2024 will be slow. Unless we have another surprise, 2023 was somewhat of a surprise.” Liu also pushed back on assertions made in previous years that the pandemic would lead to a major recession. He said that the stronger-than-expected growth in 2023 showed signs that a drastic recession was avoided. He added that, going forward, the higher interest rate could slow down economic growth across the U.S. next year, but might allow for a “soft landing,” where issues like inflation and unemployment improve without drastic interruptions to the economy. Overall, he said that employment, in many sectors, has rebounded from the COVID-19 pandemic, with growth surpassing pre-pandemic levels. One major exception is the mining industry, he said. “Leisure, hospitality, and even retail, many other services, actually their employment is higher than pre-COVID levels,” he said. “So, overall, Wyoming’s total employment is already 2% higher than pre-COVID levels. ... So that means our economy has been more diverse than pre-COVID.” The main factor where things are decreasing, Liu pointed out, was in taxable sales, which he attributed to federal interest rates and the decline of mining in Wyoming. title: “Chapters of My Life”: An Intriguing and Motivating Story of Life Triumph Leading to Transformation | User | bigspringherald.com
text:
Tommy Sipper writes his memoir titled Chapters of My Life that takes readers through a memorable and evocative of his growing up in a rural South Alabama town. Readers are offered a window through which they view the author’s complexities of adolescence, adulthood, and being a family man.
In the background of the winding creek and sprawling fields in the heart of the Deep South, Tommy expertly provides a well-detailed story of his formative years. This section of the book offers the essence of rural life and the tremendous impact it has made on his life. The idyllic nature of the rural town of Alabama is filled with happiness and lots of storytelling that contributed to shaping his character.
As the narrative of the book is unfurled, readers are invited into Tommy’s world to see the challenges and opportunities he encountered on his way through adolescence into adulthood. Chapters of My Life provides readers with a reflection on the benefits of resilience and happiness. According to one of the narratives of this book, happiness is a journey, not a destination.
Readers who did not grow up in the South are bound to enjoy this book. Reviews from readers have been raving and glowing. Some readers describe Chapters of My Life as relative and inspiring while others see it as a testament of resilience and optimism. This memoir resonates well with readers looking to tap into the transformative power of storytelling.
Tommy celebrates the spirit of unity and the enduring bonds of a community through this memoir. His unwavering spirit to connect with his roots is enthralling and encourages readers to take a leaf out of his book.
Growing up Tommy came across challenges and adversities. He tells his endurance story to encourage others to persevere in the face of adversity. The author also tells the beautiful story of raising a family.
The author’s incredible storytelling ability contributes to making this memoir unique and among the bestselling memoirs.
Chapters of My Life is available to be purchased on major online retail stores such as Amazon . You can grab a copy today and take a walk down the memory lane all the way to the rural South Alabama town with Tommy Speller.

Qué grande el excoletas por haber retratado a toda la escoria fascista, aplastapobres y vendepatrias de este país. Todavía se sabe que escuece viendo que tienen a bastardos malpagados defendiendo lo indefendible por doquier. Son tan tiernos.

Alvise es un tentetieso para salir de Ayuso. Me dan ganas de votar cada noticia de Alvise SPAM a partir de ahora.

Está claro que se hizo la foto de graduación con créditos pendientes y ahora va de que ha terminado la carrera.

author: KSBW via CNN Newsource
title: Missing hiker found alive after being lost for 10 days in mountains
text: SANTA CRUZ COUNTY, Calif. (KSBW) - A missing hiker was finally rescued after he was lost for 10 days in the Santa Cruz Mountains of California. The 34-year-old man was only going for a three-hour hike when he disappeared. “I didn’t bring anything because I thought I was doing a three-hour hike to go to work,” Lukas McClish, the rescued hiker, said. He was lost in the woods for nine nights and 10 days, shirtless with only a flashlight and folding scissors. It would be more than a week before the raggedy-looking hiker would be found. “So, I kind of just hiked. Each day, I go up a canyon, down a canyon to the next waterfall, sit down by the waterfall, drink water out of my boot,” Lukas McClish recalled. It was a Tuesday when Lukas McClish went for a hike in Boulder Creek and ended up getting lost. “I felt comfortable the whole time I was out there. I wasn’t worried about it,” Lukas McClish said. “I had a mountain lion that was following me, but it was cool. It kept its distances. I think it was just somebody watching over me.” The problem was that Lukas McClish didn’t tell anyone where he was going. By the time Father’s Day rolled around on Sunday, his family started worrying and filed a missing person’s report. The search was on then. “Some nights, although, I just had to trust God that he was going to be OK, and that was hard to do some nights when we would go to bed at night because I would worry about where he was, where he was sleeping and how cold he was and where he was if he was alive,” Diane McClish, the hiker’s mother, said. Lukas McClish drank from water from creeks, ate wild berries and slept on a wet bed of leaves all while yelling for help and thinking of his next meal. “‘Just help. Help, I’m over here.’ Or, ‘Is anybody out there?’” Lukas McClish remembered saying while he was lost. “I want a burrito or a taco bowl. That’s what I thought about every day when I, after the first five days, when I started to kind of realize that I might be in over my head.” But on Thursday afternoon, someone finally heard his cries for help. The Boulder Creek Fire Department deployed a drone and spotted his location. A K-9 tracked him down and Lukas McClish was escorted out of a remote canyon, finally reunited with family. “Met a lot of people because I had more people come to me and tell me how much they love my son and how they just hoped that we would find him,” Diane McClish said. “I didn’t realize that so many people in this town love Luke.” Fortunately, Lukas McClish had no major injuries.
